12	Evaluating de-packaging technologies to remove film plastics from food	2020-09-28 12:17:20.091773	2020-11-18 15:11:37.524353	1	\N	The US Environmental Protection Agency (US EPA) is committed to the establishment of reproducible, representative, accurate, precise methods for micro-plastics (MPs) and nano-plastics (NPs) analysis. These methods also include appropriate quality assurance/quality control (QA/QC) for micro-plastics (MPs) and nano-plastics (NPs) sample collection; extraction from food, food waste, surface and drinking water, dust, sediment and tissue samples. This information will assist in improving micro-plastics (MPs) and nano-plastics (NPs) size, shape and chemical composition characterization, and quantification, particularly for particles in the micron scale size for which information is limited and is relevant to quantifying human and ecological exposure risks.\r\n\r\nThe United States government is committed to reducing food waste by 50% by 2030. To divert food waste from landfills, the US EPA’s Office of Research and Development’s (ORD), Center for Environmental Solutions & Emergency Response (CESER) promotes anaerobic digestion and composting of food waste. However, contamination of food waste with packaging (including film plastics) may complicate composting and anaerobic digestion operations and decrease the market desirability and safety of land application of the compost and digestate resulting from food waste.\r\n\r\nORD in collaboration with our partners within the Agency are developing technologies to test for micro-plastics (MPs) and nano-plastics (NPs) in assessing their impact and the role they have at the interface and within a food waste system. This project, I am leading, involves a team that is developing methods for extracting, characterizing, quantifying and understanding the effects of micro- and nano-plastics (MPs & NPs) in food waste. By studying the potential impacts of these micro- and nano-plastics (MPs & NPs) we can identify how to improve the performance of de-packaging equipment available on the market. We are looking to work with community partners to aid us in the characterization of plastics in food waste streams. This project is designed to have samples collected from 5 - 10 cities across the US, along with 10 food de-packaging facilities, such as restaurants and groceries chosen in each city. The samples will be shipped to the EPA Cincinnati Laboratories, where they will be qualitatively and quantitatively analyzed for micro- and nano-plastics (MPs & NPs). The results from this study will be useful to EPA, restaurant and commercial kitchen operators, food retailers, composters, and wastewater treatment facility staff across the US as they seek to exclude plastics (including micro- and nano-plastics (MPs & NPs)) from the food waste stream.	5231859
